orary ideas of national identity are tied to particular versions of history that valorize white masculinity and ignores oppression and resistance. Through her explanation and analysis of what she calls the historical imaginary, Guthrie offers new ways of attempting to combat harmful myths of the past through the imaginative engagements they have dominated for so long.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHistory in popular culturezUnited States. 0aImaginary (Philosophy). 0aMass media and historyzUnited States. 0aNational characteristics, American. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ahistorical analysis, fictional analysis, historical fiction, american historical fiction, contemporary consumerism, historical media, Walt Disney World, Quentin Tarantino, national identity, american identity, television in america, historical imaginary, time travel television series, flat screeen tvs, quentin tarantino movies, classic movies, top 10 classic movies, alternate histories in fiction, fictional history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978818842?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978818842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978818842/original  a978-3-11-079130-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK